ion and professional reserve they employed in their occupations. Along the way, these editors kicked off a middle-class sexual revolution in which white-collar professionals imagined they could control sexuality through management science. Obscenity is often presented as self-shattering and subversive, but with this provocative work Carroll calls into question some of the most sensational claims about obscenity, suggesting that when transgression becomes a sign of class distinction, we must abandon the idea that obscenity always overturns hierarchies and disrupts social order.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAnticensorship activistszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCensorshipzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEditorsxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aErotic literaturexPublishingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMiddle class menxBooks and readingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aObscenity (Law)zUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPornographyxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aUS literature.  acensorship.  aclass.  aeditors.  agender.  aobscenity.  aprofessional-managerial class.  apublishing.  asexuality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073914540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362949340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503629493423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503629493/original  a978-3-11-073914-5  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles